We're running bamboo remote agents in docker containers, and noticed the log files were not encoded correctly (strange characters), this was fixed by setting environment variable {{LANG=C.UTF-8}}

However when clicking the 'view' link to open a log directly in the browser, the encoding is also not correct for URLs /download/JOB/build_logs/JOB_ID.log

Is there a better fix then updating mimetypes.xml with the following
{code}
    <mime-mapping>
        <extension>log</extension>
        <mime-type>text/plain;charset=UTF-8</mime-type>
    </mime-mapping>
{code}

Thanks!

BAM-13584 added support for matching plan display name downloading of artifacts. Which is greatly helpful but not always what is desired. It would be much more useful to have arbitrary plan branch selection in the artifact download task.

{panel:title=Edited 2017-11-09}
This article might help to workaround this problem: [How to download another plan branch artifacts to the current plan \- Atlassian Documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bamkb/how-to-download-another-plan-branch-artifacts-to-the-current-plan-939710384.html]
{panel}

{panel:title=BAM-15104}
When a user configures an Artifact Download Task we should give the possibility to specify a target branch of the plan that produced the artifact.

There could be 3 options:
[] Pick the artifact from the default branch of the parent plan
[] Pick the artifact from the same branch as the current plan
[] Pick the artifact from the branch <branch> of the parent plan
{panel}

{panel:title=BAM-13794}
Enable Artifact Downloader to download artifacts from the same branch if existed; download from a specific branch if the same branch plan not existed
{panel}

Markdown files (*.md) with inline PHP code sections aren't highlighted unless the opening <?php tag is present - this forces people to add the opening <?php tag which can be extremely misleadning, as there is no way to tell the difference betwen an example code fragment and an example file.

For example, this is a file example, which does get highlighted:

{noformat}
```php
<?php

require "_bootstrap.php";
```
{noformat}

And this is a code sample, which does not get highlighed:

{noformat}
```php
$router = $container->get(Router::class);
```
{noformat}

It's extremely problematic, as this forces authors to write misleading examples such as:

{noformat}
```php
<?php

$router = $container->get(Router::class);
```
{noformat}

The latter is clearly not valid as a file, but we can't tell the difference between code samples and file samples...

It's also inconsistent with Github-flavored Markdown, which is where this syntax originated.

Please, can you fix this asap?

